name: Victor Wembanyama
playerOutlook: Wembanyama joined the NBA last season with the kind of hype not seen since LeBron James entered the league two decades earlier. After a solid first couple of months as the Spurs' starting power forward, Wemby moved to center and his production exploded. By the end of the season he established himself as a nightly 25-10-5 threat that also led the league in blocks, and he is capable of grabbing two steals and knocking down two treys a night. He even shoots great percentages from the line. Wemby took the sky-high expectations and blew right past them, and enters this season challenging Nikola Jokic for top overall pick in points leagues and an iron-clad lock on the top spot in category leagues, where his blocked shots and all-around game put him on an island as the No. 1 pick.

name: Luka Doncic
playerOutlook: Doncic came within decimal points of average a 34-10-10 triple double last season, and led the entire league in fantasy points scored per game. At only 25 years old, Doncic is still on the upward trajectory of his career and getting better. He set career-highs in points, assists, 3-pointers, steals and free throw percentage last season while leading the Mavericks to the NBA FInals. He learned to play in the same backcourt with Kyrie Irving with both thriving, and with the addition of a shooter like Klay Thompson, Doncic could have both more space to operate and also more effective finishers for his assists.

name: Nikola Jokic
playerOutlook: Jokic has been the top fantasy scorer in the NBA for four straight seasons, including by 461 fantasy points over second-place Luka Doncic last season. Jokic has a combination of incredible per-game production (4-year averages of 26.1 PPG, 12.2 RPG, 8.7 APG, 1.4 SPG, 1.1 3PG, 0.8 BPG) and durability (4-year average only six games missed per season). The Nuggets have maintained largely the same top-four players for several seasons, and Jokic remains one of the most consistently elite ringleaders in the league as he aims for his fourth MVP in five years.

name: Shai Gilgeous-Alexander
playerOutlook: Gilgeous-Alexander is coming off a season so special that he received votes for NBA Most Improved Player despite having finished in the top-5 in the MVP vote the season before! SGA has settled into his role as score-first playmaking creator for the Thunder, notching consecutive seasons averaging 30+ points and coming off career-bests of 6.2 APG, 2.0 STP and 53.5 FG%. He led the NBA in total steals last season while also notching just over a 3-pointer and just under a block per game, making him just as elite in category leagues as in points leagues. SGA projects to be the first guard drafted in fantasy hoops leagues, and has a chance of joining the top big men in surpassing the 60 FP/game threshold.

name: Tyrese Haliburton
playerOutlook: Haliburton was in the midst of a giant leap in his fourth season when injury struck. Through his first 30 games, Haliburton was averaging 24.9 PPG (50.1 FG%, 86.3 FT%, 40.8 3P%), 12.7 APG, 4.1 RPG, 3.6 3PG, 1.0 SPG and 0.7 BPG with only 2.5 TO. Those numbers had him firmly in the top-5 of fantasy hoops rankings with a chance to challenge for the top spot. Unfortunately, he injured his hamstring in January and had to miss a lot of time, and even when he returned he was clearly not the same physically. If Haliburton returns to health and form, he could challenge Shai Gilgeous-Alexander for the most productive guard in fantasy basketball.

name: Joel Embiid
playerOutlook: Embiid was one of only three players to average more than 60 fantasy points per game last season, and statistically he was ahead of his NBA MVP-winning numbers from the previous season. Unfortunately, injury struck and limited Embiid to 39 games, the fewest since his rookie season. Embiid has reportedly lost a significant amount of weight this offseason in the attempt to put less strain on his legs and maintain better health this season. If he can do so, Embiid would be on the short list of players capable of leading the league in fantasy points. He has averaged more than a 30-10 double-double in three straight seasons, dished a career-best 5.6 APG last season, and generated between 1.2 and 1.7 steals, 3-pointers and blocks per game last season to boot. He is an elite prospect in both points and category leagues. But, Embiid has never played more than 68 games in his NBA career, and the question marks about his durability are why Embiid projects to more of a mid-late first round fantasy hoops prospect instead of the top-4 guy his game would support.

name: Anthony Davis
playerOutlook: Davis is coming off the most durable season of his career, playing 76 games for the first time. The result was powerful, with Davis scoring the fifth-most fantasy points in the league. Davis' game has always been extremely productive, and as he moved to starting center and took on more team leadership responsibilities for the Lakers, he amped up that production even more. But it was the number of games that told the story. Davis had only averaged 48 games played per season in his first four campaigns with the Lakers. If he is able to turn in consecutive 70+ game seasons for only the second time in his career, Davis would be even more valuable than his borderline top-10 fantasy hoops valuation.

name: Donovan Mitchell
playerOutlook: Mitchell agreed to a three-year, super-max extension with the Cavaliers this offseason and returns as the clear-cut leader of the team with no distractions this season. An explosive combo-guard who can score inside and out, Mitchell notched career bests of 6.1 APG, 5.1 RPG, 1.8 SPG and 0.5 BPG last season after notching career-highs of 28.3 PPG and 3.6 3PG on 48.4 FG% and 86.7 FT% the season before. Still in his athletic peak at 28 years old, Mitchell has the potential to match or surpass these marks in the upcoming campaign.

name: Jayson Tatum
playerOutlook: Tatum has averaged at leasst 26.0 PPG, 7.0 RPG, 4.0 APG, 2.9 3PG and 1.0 SPG with eight or fewer missed games in four consecutive seasons. He is a model of consistency at extremely high levels, and was able to keep his production elite last season even in the Celtics' star-studded lineup that included two new All Stars. Tatum is still only 26 years old, still ramping up to his peak NBA years, and looks poised for another season delivering first round fantasy hoops production.

name: Anthony Edwards
playerOutlook: Edwards is coming off his best season, making All NBA Second Team and earning MVP votes in the regular season before aking the league by storm in the playoffs. In his last two postseason runs, Edwards has averaged 28.5 PPG (48.2 FG%, 82.3 FT%), 6.5 RPG, 6.2 APG, 2.9 3PG, 1.6 SPG and 0.9 BPG. He hasn't shown yet that he can perform at that level in the regular season, but he's only 23 years old and has improved significantly each season. Edwards is the unquestioned leader in Minnesota, and with Karl-Anthony Towns traded he will likely stake an even larger claim to his alpha wolf status this season. First round pick in both fantasy hoops formats.

name: Trae Young
playerOutlook: Young has spent the last two seasons putting up strong numbers while coexisting in the same backcourt with fellow All-Star point guard Dejounte Murray. With Murray off the roster and Young entering his peak years at age 26, Young could be poised for his best campaign. Young has increased his assist numbers every season of his career, up to 10.8 APG last season, and he averaged 28.4 PPG in 2021-22 before Murray's arrival. Both 30-10 and league-lead in assists are in play for Young this season.

name: Chet Holmgren
playerOutlook: Holmgren turned in an epic rookie season, battling Victor Wembanyama for much of the year for Rookie of the Year honors. Though he eventually finished second in that race, Holmgren established himself as a nightly double-double threat with 20-10 upside as soon as this season. Holmgren is also one of the best shotblockers in the league, made 1.6 3-pointers per game and even notched almost a steal per night. These contributions in the more difficult to gain categories, particularly the blocks, make Holmgren a better prospect in category leagues than in points. With projections to improve in his second campaign, Holmgren ranks in the top-35 in points leagues, but as a top-15 and potential second-rounder in category leagues.

name: Giannis Antetokounmpo
playerOutlook: Antetokounmpo has finished in the top-4 of the MVP vote for six straight seasons, and last season has an argument for his best. He averaged more than 30 PPG for the second time, but on a career-best 61.1 FG%. He also set a new personal record with 6.5 APG, and added just over a steal and a block. In points leagues, Antetokounpo is a clear top-5 pick with an argument for top-3, but in category leagues his high-volume, low-percentage free throws and lack of conssistent 3-pointers drops him to the low teens in the rankings.

name: LaMelo Ball
playerOutlook: Ball was the Rookie of the Year in 2020-21, then the next season finished seventh in the league in fantasy points scored. His scoring, assists and steals per game have all increased since then, but he has played only 58 of the 164 games in the two seasons since as he has battled with severe injuries to both ankles. Ball is healthy for the start of training camp and is expected to wear braces on both ankles as a preventative measure this season, and if he is able to stay healthy he has top-10 fantasy production upside in both points-based and category leagues.

name: Scottie Barnes
playerOutlook: Barnes took a major step forward in his third season, establishing himself as the new franchise player on the Raptors as they decided to move on from both Pascal Siakam and OG Anunoby. Barnes exploded past his previous career marks in every category, with a 20/8/6 statline with still quite a bit of upside to grow. The 23-year old also contributed in the sparser categories, averaging 1.7 3PG, 1.5 BPG and 1.3 SPG to give himself even more value in category leagues (borderline first/second-round) than points (second round).

name: Domantas Sabonis
playerOutlook: Sabonis finished with the sxith-most fantasy points in the league last season through a combination of an excellent all-around offensive game and outstanding durability. After playing 79 games two seasons ago, Sabonis played in every game last season. He also led the NBA in rebounds at 13.7 RPG, and when you factor in his also career-best 8.2 APG, Sabonis has become a nightly triple-double threat. Sabonis doesn't contribute a lot to the defensive categories for a center, and he also hits less than a half a 3-pointer per game, which weakens his case for the first round in rotisserie formats. Sabonis projects to a top-10 fantasy prospects in points leagues, but is more like top-20 in category leagues.

name: Stephen Curry
playerOutlook: Curry is the last Splash Brother standing for the Warriors after Klay Thompson left for the Mavericks during the offseason. Curry had an eventful summer of his own, catching fire in the medal games of the Olympics to help lead team USA to the gold. His shooting expedition demonstrated that, even at 36 years old in his 16th NBA season Curry is still the best shooter in the NBA with a proclivity for going nova-hot at any given moment. In the four seasons since missing most of 2019-20 injured, Curry has averaged 28.2 PPG, 5.8 APG, 5.3 RPG, 4.9 3PG and 1.0 SPG in 33.9 MPG. Those numbers are all in play for this season as well, though he likely plays fewer minutes and therefore produces slightly less volume across the board. The question will be durability, with last season's 74 games played marking the first time Curry played 70 or more games since the 2016-17 season. Curry's mega-volume 3-point shooting is more valuable in category leagues, leading him to a top-20/second round valuation in category leagues vs more of a top-25/third round valuation in points leagues.

name: Karl-Anthony Towns
playerOutlook: The Towns trade to the Knicks appears to be the rare win-win deal for all involved. Towns was one of three very good centers on the Timberwolves, forcing him to play out of position at power forward and shift his game more to the perimeter at both ends. This didn't play into Towns' strengths, and he simultaneously had to learn to play as the second option as Anthony Edwards took control of the offense. With the Knicks, Towns returns to center on a team with few other healthy big men. No longer having to share the paint with Rudy Gobert, Towns' rebuond and shotblocking numbers could return to the 12+ boards and 1.5 blocks he averaged in his first four NBA seasons. And even though the Knicks have several plus scorers, they lack both interior scoring options and some perimeter shooting with DiVincenzo gone so KAT should have the green light from all his favorite spots. Add in a natural two-man pick-and-roll/pop synergy with Jalen Brunson, and Towns projects to right around a top-20 fantasy prospect in both points and category leagues.

name: James Harden
playerOutlook: Though the impression was that Harden was in Joel Embiid's shadow in Philadelphia and that he returned to his usual levels once he "escaped" to the Clippers, the truth is that Harden's numbers went down across the board once he arrived in Los Angeles. He took his fewest shots since he became a starter more than a decade ago, and scored his fewest points since winning Sixth Man of the Year in 2011-12. His assists, rebounds, 3-pointers and steals also dropped year-over-year. While part of this may be due to age, with Harden entering his age 35 season, he was also on a loaded Clippers team featuring several other star talents. With Paul George and Russell Westbrook out of town, Harden may have to carry a larger role with closer to his typical usage this season. Harden's volume 3-point shooting, solid steals and even a near-block per game make him a better prospect in category leagues, top-20, than his top-30 valuation in points leagues.

name: LeBron James
playerOutlook: James played 71 games last season, the most he's played since the 2017-18 season. The big question is, can James, in his age 40 season, turn in a second consecutive durable season after only averaging 55 games played in his first five seasons with the Lakers. If the answer is yes, LeBron would be a top-10 prospect in points leagues with his averages remaining at 26 PPG, 8 APG, 7 RPG, 2 3PG and a combined 2 blocks/steals per game even in season 21 of his career. More modest projections of games played give James a top-15 valuation in points leagues, but top-20 in category leagues where his free throw percentage brings him down a notch.

name: De'Aaron Fox
playerOutlook: Fox has always been one of the quickest players off the dribble in the NBA, but he averaged a career-best 26.6 PPG last season in part because of a dramatically improved 3-point shot. His 2.9 3PG were almost twice what he made the previous season, and his 36.9 3P% was the second-highest mark of his career. Fox nominally plays point guard, but with Domantas Sabonis acting as the primary hub of the offense, Fox is more free to work off-ball or get the ball in advantageous positions to attack. He also set a personal best with 2.0 SPG, and his all-around game makes him a top-20 prospect in fantasy hoops leagues.

name: Kevin Durant
playerOutlook: Durant is coming off an outstanding season, characterized by his playing in 75 games. This was the most games he had played sinc ethe 2018-19 season before he tore his Achilles tendon, and only the second time since the 2014-15 season he missed fewer than 10 games. When available on the court, Durant remains one of the greatest shooter-scorers in NBA history. He shot 52.3% from the field and 85.6% from the line, the 11th straight season he surpassed those marks, and his 27.1 PPG marked the 15th streaight season he has scored more than 25 PPG. Durant also blocks about a shot, grabs about a steal, and makes more than two 3-pointers per game, contributions that make him elite in category leagues as well. The main question with Durant is whether, at age 36 in his 17th season, he can produce a secong straight durable season. If so, his actual value would be even higher than the just-outside-the-top-20 rankings that project him missing more time.

name: Ja Morant
playerOutlook: Morant missed the first 25 games last season due to suspension, played a couple weeks and then missed the rest of the season with a shoulder injury. He enters this season ready to try to reclaim the All NBA form that saw him get votes for MVP just two seasons ago. Morant remains perhaps the most athleticly explosive guard in the NBA, with demonstrated ability to score in the upper-20s of points with near double-digit assists and about six boards on a nightly basis. Not the greatest shooter, Morant still knocks down about 1.5 treys and grabs about a steal per game. Morant is a worthy late first/early second round pick in points leagues, but in category leagues he drops about a round due to the lack of defensive production.

name: Damian Lillard
playerOutlook: Lillard was traded to Milwaukee last season with high hopes, but in Year 1 things didn't go as planned. Lillard and Giannis Antetkounmpo never seemed to find any synergy, and Antetokounpo's extremely high usage forced Lillard into more of a finisher role than he had typically been used to. The result was Lillard's second lowest scoring average since 2015, and his second-lowest field goal percentage since 2016. Lillard was also down about a 3-pointer from the season before. Lillard reportedly also had some off-court issues he was dealing with last season, and with a year of experience together the situation seems ripe for him to bounce-back this season. Lillard projects as a third-round pick in fantasy hoops drafts.

name: Jalen Brunson
playerOutlook: Brunson has blossomed into a legitimate MVP candidate with the Knicks, as attested to by his fifth place finish in the vote last season. His 28.7 PPG, 6.7 APG and 2.7 3PG last season all represented career-high marks, and he also played in at least 77 games for the second time in three seasons. The Knicks have been busy this offseason, trading away Julius Randle and Donte DiVincenzo but bringing back Karl-Anthony Towns and Mikal Bridges. Brunson should continue to be the lead dog, but with more consistent scorers around him he might lose a bit of scoring volume in exchange for more assist opportunities. He also should mesh particularly well with Towns on offense as a big man pick-and-roll/pop partner who also is one of the best 3-point shooting bigs in the league. Defenses will have to respect Towns enough that it should free Brunson up for consistent good looks, in a dimension he hasn't otherwise been able to explore with the Knicks. Burnson doesn't have a big statistical footprint on defense, which lowers his category ranking to top-25, but in points leagues Brunson projects just outside of the top-10 and is a late-first/early-second round draft prospect.

name: Cade Cunningham
playerOutlook: Cunningham was the top overall pick in the 2021 NBA Draft, and he's played well enough to earn the five-year max rookie extenstion he signed with the Pistons in July. His main issue to date, though, has been availability. Cunningham has only played in 138 of the 246 games in his three-year career, and this has limited his total output and likely slowed his development. Even still, he made major strides in year 3, setting new career bests across the board on offense in both volume and efficiency and establishing himself as one of the better scorer-distributors in the league. Cade has the size of a forward but the game of a point guard, and this versatility makes him a nightly mismatch that he continues to get better at exploiting. Cunningham is a top-30 fantasy hoops prospect this season, but with health and continued development his upside is even higher than his projections.

name: Desmond Bane
playerOutlook: Bane has improved markedly in every year he's been in the NBA, culminating last season with career-best marks of 23.7 PPG, 5.5 APG, 3.3 3PG and 0.5 BPG. The two biggest question marks for him moving forward are about healthâ€¦he's missed 64 games in the last two seasons...and how his usage will be impacted with Ja Morant back full-time. Bane's shots and assist opportunities could dip a bit this season, but if his scoring efficiency and 3-pointers increase it could all even out. He enters the season as a top-40 prospect in points leagues, but closer to top-25 in category leagues due to his volume 3-point shooting.

name: Devin Booker
playerOutlook: Booker is coming off a season playing largely point guard for the  Suns, leading to a a career-best 6.9 APG. This season, the Suns brought in Tyus Jones to run the point and allow Booker to move back to his primary strength as a scorer. Booker is one of the most efficient shooter-scorers in the league, averaging 27.4 PPG on 49.3 FG%, 35.8 3P% and 87.2 FT% in the last two seasons. With Kevin Durant and Bradley Beal also drawing defensive attention, Booker is allowed to operate largely 1-on-1 and generate his offense. Booker projects to a top-20 fantasy option in points leagues, but his lack of defensive-stat contributions drops him just outside the top-25 in the categorty rankings.

name: Jaren Jackson Jr.
playerOutlook: Jackson leaned into a different aspect of his game last season, and it will be interesting to see if he can combine his two approaches this season. Last season, Jackson was relied upon as a primary scoring option with Ja Morant out, and he responded with by-far a career-best 22.5 PPG, and also notched personal records of 2.3 APG and 1.2 SPG. But his 5.5 RPG were his lowest since his second season and his 1.6 BPG were about half of his league-leading 3.0 BPG from the season before. With Morant back, will Jackson lean back into his defense but still maintain a bit more offense? If so, he could outperform his top-70 valuation in points leagues. But he really shines in category leagues, particularly when he's blocking shots, and he is a viable late third/early fourth round prospect in those leagues.

name: Paul George
playerOutlook: George ended his run next to Kawhi Leonard on his hometown Clippers to move east, signing with the 76ers this offseason. George is a theoretical perfect fit as the third member of a big three also featuring former MVP and dominant big man Joel Embiid and reigning Most Improved Player and All Star guard Tyrese Maxey. George, the 6-9 Swiss army knife that can do everything on the basketball court, provides shooting and spacing to open up space for Embiid to work, a finisher to score off Maxey's dimes, and a defender capable of defending elite wings and generating positive defensive stats. George also played with two great offensive talents last season in Leonard and James Harden, so should be able to coexist in the 76ers' regime without losing much in the way of volume. His biggest question mark is durability; before playing 74 games last season, George had averaged only 47 games played in the four previous seasons (note: two of those seasons shortened by COVID).

name: Kyrie Irving
playerOutlook: Irving has evolved his game to fit next to Luka Doncic, the highest usage player in the NBA. He is able to do so by dint of being simultaneously one of the best high-efficiency/high-volume shooters in the league as well as one of the greatest creators off the bounce in league history. The combo allows Irving to maintain a scoring average in the mid-to-upper 20s per game with polished all-around numbers that make him one of the top-25 fantasy hoops producers on a game-to-game basis. The biggest question is always availability, with Irving missing an average of 34 games in his last five seasons.

name: Kawhi Leonard
playerOutlook: Leonard responded to the NBA's new rule against load management by playing in 68 games, his highest game count since the 2016-17 season. On the downside, after playing in 68 of the first 74 games, Leonard did fall injured and miss the rest of the regular season and much of the playoffs. The durability concerns are the biggest factor that keep leonard as a top-50 prospect instead of the top-25 his per-game stats would suggest. Leonard remains an excellent scorer on excellent efficiency, a strong source of rebounds and assists from the frontcourt, and a 3-and-D player capable of averaging close to five combined 3-pointers, steals and blocks. He thus has even higher value in category leagues than points.

name: Paolo Banchero
playerOutlook: Banchero was the Rookie of the Year in 2022-23, then followed that up by earning his first All Star nod as a sophomore. Statistically, his improvements were incremental but indicated good offensive development. He scored a few more points per game while simultaneously increasing his shooting percentages from both the field and the 3-point line, and he did it as the clear-cut first option that opponents keyed on. Banchero also increased his diestribution, up over five assists per game, illustrating his evolution toward more of a point-forward role. Banchero notched 1.5 3-pointers, almost a steal and just over half-a-block per game, but an improvement in particularly blocked shots could make a big difference in his category-league projections. As-is, he ranks as a top-25 prospect in points leagues but closer to top-35 in category leagues.

name: Tyrese Maxey
playerOutlook: Maxey stormed onto the scene last season, winning NBA Most Improved Player and earning his first All Star selection. Maxey is an explosive scorer-playmaker that will still be only 23 when the season starts, so he has plenty of upside to improve. However, the 76ers brought in another elite offensive engine this offseason in Paul George to form a big three with Maxey and former MVP Joel Embiid. It is likely that Maxey may improve, but still see his volume decrease as his teammates need to eat as well. Neverheless, Maxey projects to top-25 value in points leagues, slightly ahead of his top-35 valuation in category leagues where his lack of defensive stats nudges his ranking down a notch.

name: Lauri Markkanen
playerOutlook: Markkanen has blossomed into a legitimate star in his two seasons in Utah, averaging 24.4 PPG, 8.4 RPG and 3.1 3PG while coming within a decimal point of the magical 50/40/90 shooting percentages. Markkanen is the frontcourt franchise player, and his offensive gravity makes life easier on the rest of his teammates. Markkanen projects as a borderline top-40 producer in points leagues, but his shooting is more valuable in category leagues where he is more like top-35. The main question for Markkanen is availability; he has missed at least 14 games in every season of his career and sat out 27 games last season.

name: Bam Adebayo
playerOutlook: Adebayo is growing into the best player on the Heat, at least during the regular season. He has been within decimal points of averaging 20 points and 10 rebounds in three straight seasons, and he's also a plus passer for a big man that can contribute 4-5 assists per game. Adebayo has shot greater than 52 percent from the field and 75 percent from the line in four straight seasons. But while Adebayo has finished top-5 in the Derfensive Player of the Year vote five straight seasons, he doesn't block a full shot per game. This hurts him in category rankings, where he measures out top-40 vs top-30 in points leagues.

name: Myles Turner
playerOutlook: Turner has settled into his role as a shooter-scorer-shotblocker at center for the Pacers. Playing off Tyrese Haliburton and the shots he can create, Turner averages in the upper-teens of points with about 1.5 treys per night. He also blocks two shots per game, though his value really peaks in the years that number is closer to three. He isn't a big rebounder for a center, but in the new Pacers frontcourt he cedes some of the boards to Pascal Siakam but assumes a heavier rim protection role. Turner is a top-60 prospect in points leagues, but his shot-blocking makes him top-40 in category leagues.

name: Brook Lopez
playerOutlook: Lopez has a unique combination of skills at this pointi n his career. He is a center that only averages about five rebounds per game, but he is one of the best shotblockers in the league, knocks down about two 3-pointers per game and scores in the low-teens on solid percentages. That combo is much more valuable in category leagues where blocks and treys are harder-to-fill categories, making Lopez project to top-40 value vs top-100 in points leagues.

name: Alperen Sengun
playerOutlook: Sengun has made significant leaps in production in each of his three NBA seasons, and his Year 3 earned him a third place finish in the Most Improved Player vote. Sengun is a big man offensive hub in the mold of Nikola Jokic or Domantas Sabonis, generating 21.1 PPG and 5.0 APG last season but with upside to increase those numbers as his game improves. He is also a strong rebounder, finishing with averages of nine or more boards in two straight seasons. Sengun isn't a big shotblocker for a center, averaging just under one per game, but he does generate more than a steal and almost a block per game. The question this season centers around whether the Rockets will continue to build their offense around him, or whether Jalen Green's superstar turn last season after Sengun's injury absence will shift more responsibility his way. Current projections have Sengun as a borderline top-25 prospect in points leagues, but more like a top-40 in category leagues where his lack of blocks hinders his ranking.

name: Jalen Green
playerOutlook: Green began last season slowly, with new Rockets head coach Ime Udoka publicly calling for more maturity from the talented young wing and the team shifting their offensive focus to center Alperen Sengun. But, the Rockets went on a late season run that surprisingly brought them back into postseason contention even after Sengun was shut down, and Green was the epicenter of the excellent play. During a span in which the Rockets won 13 of 15 games and got within breathing distance of overtaking the Warriors for the last play-in slot, Green averaged 29.2 PPG (48.8 FG%, 78.2 FT%), 6.2 RPG, 4.3 3PG, 3.7 APG and 1.3 SPG. Those numbers are what the Rockets envisioned when they made Green the numer three overall pick in the 2021 NBA Draft, and the question is whether Green can replicate and sustain that level of production in Year 4. His current rankings, which factor his upside in, have him as a top-35 prospect in points leagues and top-40 in category leagues.

name: Dejounte Murray
playerOutlook: Murray has spent the last two seasons in a backcourt with another All-Star point guard in Trae Young, and while both were still able to thrive next to one another there's no question their overlapping skillsets limited both players' upside. After being dealt to the Pelicans this offseason, Murray has the chance to bounce-back to the type of peripheral numbers he produced in his last season with the Spurs: 9.2 APG and 8.3 RPG. The Pelicans didn't have a true point guard in thieir main unit, so Murray should be a high-usage creator for Zion Williamson, Brandon Ingram and CJ McCollum. The Pelicans were a middle-of-the-pack rebounding team, so Murray's athleticism and timing could make him one of the leading guards on the glass this season. Murray also has efforts of 2.6 3PG and 2.0 SPG in the last three seasons. If he can replicate his 3-year highs across the boards, Murray has the upside to outplay his current top-35 fantasy hoops valuation.

name: Rudy Gobert
playerOutlook: Gobert has shared the center spot with Karl-Anthony Towns since coming to the Timberwolves two seasons ago. His scoring, rebounding and blocked shots all suffered slightly, but with Towns now traded for Julius Randle that could change this season. Randle is a pure power forward at both ends of the court, which should open up space for Gobert to get more paint touches on offense and to patrol the rim more closely on defense. Gobert projects to about a fifth round pick in both fantasy hoops formats.

name: Jamal Murray
playerOutlook: In his second full season since returning from ACL injury, Murray notched career-bests of 21.2 PPG, 6.5 APG and 0.7 BPG. He also set personal records for scoring efficiency, shooting 48.1 percent from the field and 42.5 percent from behind the arc. Murray's skillset and mentality work perfectly as the second option on the Nuggets, allowing him to operate as both a finisher and a secondary offensive hub playing off Nikola Jokic. Availability remains a question mark, with Murray having missed an average of 19 games in his last five seasons in addition to having sat the entire 2021-22 campaign.

name: Fred VanVleet
playerOutlook: VanVleet joined the Rockets last season after spending his first seven NBA seasons with the Raptors, and while he turned in his lowest scoring average (17.4 PPG) since he becamse a full-time starter, he also embraced his role as the floor general for a very young squad and notched a career-high 8.1 APG while playing a whopping 36.8 MPG, his fifth straight season over 35 MPG. VanVleet also provided strong category value with 3.1 3PG, 1.4 SPG, and even a surprising 0.8 BPG at only 6-feet tall. There are signs that VanVleet could be due for a smaller role this season, though. The Rockets chose highly regarded combo guard Reed Sheppard with the third overall pick in this summer's draft, and he could eat into VanVleet's role. Also, big picture, the Rockets start three players aged 22 or less, have another 21 year old ready for big minutes in last season's fourth overall pick Amen Thompson, and now Reed on deck. The 30-something VanVleet could eventually end up ceding time to younger teammates. VanVleet remains a top-60 prospect in points leagues, and is even higher at top-45 in category leagues due to his strong contributions to sparser categories.

name: Julius Randle
playerOutlook: Randle was traded to the Timberwolves this offseason as part of a package for Karl-Anthony Towns. He had settled into his role as the primary frontcourt scorer for the Knicks, and was a fraction under being a 25-point/10-rebound player for the past two seasons. Because he's a more natural power forward than Towns, Randle should actually fit better in the Timberwolves lineup next to Rudy Gobert than Towns did. Randle could cede a rebound or two to Gobert, but the Timberwolves' starting lineup could use a bit more aggression and scoring from the power forward slot so his shot share may remain consistent. Randle is a top-50 prospect in both fantasy hoops formats.

name: Jalen Johnson
playerOutlook: Johnson took a huge leap in his third season, moving into the Hawks' starting lineup and becoming a consistent double-double threat while contributing postiviely to almost every category. As the likely second option on the Hawks this season with Dejounte Murray gone, Johnson's production could make another significant jump this season. He has definite 20-10-5 upside, and enters the season as a top-50 fantasy hoops prospect.

name: Nikola Vucevic
playerOutlook: Vucevic is the metronome of the NBA. In his last three seasons with the Bulls, he has produced within decimal points of his averages of 17.8 PPG, 10.9 RPG, 3.3 APG, 1.4 3PG, 0.8 SPG and 0.8 BPG in at least 73 games in every campaign. Vucevic does his thing night-in and night-out, regardless of his teammates or his opponents, and he can safely be penciled in for another similar statline this season as well.

name: Nic Claxton
playerOutlook: Claxton has come within a decimal point of averaging a double-double in two straight seasons and signed a hundred-million dollar deal in the offseason to remain the Nets' franchise big man for the foreseeable future. He is a high-flyer at both ends of the court, leading to high-efficiency finishes on offense and blocked shots on defense. Claxton's poor shooting from the line and inability to knock down the 3-pointer are weaknesses in category leagues, but in points leagues he projects just outside the top-50 entering the season.

name: Jalen Williams
playerOutlook: Williams followed up a second-place finish in the Rookie of the Year race the season before with a fourth-place finish in the Most Improved Player vote as a sophomore. He improved dramatically as a scorer, flirting with becoming a 20 PPG player on excellent efficiency (54.0 FG%, 42.7 3P%, 81.4 FT%). Williams also notched 1.5 3-pointers, a bit more than a steal and 0.6 BPG as well, adding to his category-league bonafides. With another leap in improvement in Year 3, WIlliams has the upside to surpass even his current top-50 valuation and move into the true fantasy hoops elite.

name: Derrick White
playerOutlook: White had a career-season as a defender last season as the only guard in the NBA to average at least a block and a steal per game. He also set new career-bests of 2.7 3PG and 4.2 RPG, and was within decimal points of his career-highs with 15.2 PPG and 5.2 APG. As the glue-guy for the Celtics, White has become the type of across-the-board contributor that is very valuable, particularly in category-based leagues.

name: Jaylen Brown
playerOutlook: Brown sacrificed almost three field goal attempts per game last season as the Celtics welcomed Kristaps Porzingis and Jrue Holiday to the team, leading to his lowest scoring average in four seasons. Brown still managed career-best marks of 3.6 APG and 1.2 SPG, and remains a plus scorer and solid 3-point threat and rebounder among wings. He also once again showed himself to be a big-game performer with a series of efficient scoring efforts that won him both the Eastern Conference Final and NBA FInals MVP awards last season.

name: D'Angelo Russell
playerOutlook: Russell has been dealing with trade rumors for years, but he exercised his player option to remain with the Lakers again this season. His production is very consistent at this point in his career: scoring in the upper teens, just over six assists, about three boards and three 3-pointers per game. When in the zone, Russell can light it up to over 30 points with large numbers of treys on a given night, but on the whole he averages out to a productive player that's worth considering in around the sixth round of fantasy hoops drafts.

name: Mikal Bridges
playerOutlook: Bridges was an excellent role-playing glue guy in his first 4.5 NBA seasons with the Suns, but after his mid-season trade to the Nets in 2023 he exploded into a high-volume-scoring first option over the final 27 games of the season. Desipte high expectations entering last season, Bridges was unable to replicate his scoring exploits and settled into more of a player just under 20/5/4 than someone who could drop 25 a night. This season, Bridges likely returns to more of a Suns-like role for his new team, the Knicks. With Jalen Brunson and Karl-Anthony Towns as the primary offensive options, Bridges will join OG Anunoby to provide one of the better defensive forward duos in the NBA. Bridges has proven he's a plus shooter-scorer, and scoring averages in the mid-upper teens with more than 2.5 3-pointers per game are solid expectations. Bridges is also the iron-man of the NBA, having never missed a game in his career. His durable dependability and strong 3-and-D game project Bridges to around a top-50 prospect in both points and category leagues.

name: Miles Bridges
playerOutlook: Bridges missed the entire 2022-23 season due to off-court issues, but returned last season with arguably the best campaign of his career. A plus scorer as a combo forward, Bridges set personal bests in scoring (21.0 PPG), rebounds (7.3 RPG), 3-pointers (2.3 3PG) and steals (0.9 SPG) last season. Bridges is one of three primary scorers on the Hornets alongside LaMelo Ball and sophomore Brandon Miller, and with the other two starters defensive role-players there are enough shots for all three scorers to average more than 20 PPG this season.

name: Jrue Holiday
playerOutlook: Holiday is the Celtics starter that sacrificed the most offense in their star-laden starting lineup, dropping almost seven points per game on average from the previous season on his fewest shots (10.0 FGA) since his rookie year (2009-10). Holiday remains one of the best defensive guards in the league and turned in career-bests of 5.4 RPG and 0.8 BPG, along with 0.9 SPG. He also made two 3-pointers a night for the fourth time in the last five seasons.

name: CJ McCollum
playerOutlook: McCollum has been playing de facto point guard for the Pelicans since being traded there three seasons ago, but with the Pelicans bringing in Dejounte Murray this offseason it's likely McCollum moves back to his natural shooting guard slot this season. McCollum has averaged at least 20.0 PPG, 3.0 APG and 2.3 3PG for nine straight seasons, and with his emphasis shifting back to shooting and scoring he has a good chance to hit those marks a 10th straight time this season. The concern is that his scoring volume may decrease on a team featuring three other scorers also capable of scoring 20 PPG, but he could be in for one of the more efficient shooting seasons in his career as a result. The lower volume lowers McCollum's points ranking to top-70, but his high-volume 3-point shooting adds enough value that he is knocking on top-55 in category leagues.

name: Donte DiVincenzo
playerOutlook: DiVincenzo, traded to the Timberwolves from the Knicks along with Julius Randle, ranked third in the league in 3-pointers made last season, trailing only Luka Doncic and Stephen Curry. His ability to stretch the floor will make him a great kick-out option when Anthony Edwards and Randle drive to the basket for Minnesota. Whether he starts or comes off the bench, DiVincenzo is poised to make an impact. Heâ€™s a solid pick just before the double-digit rounds.

name: Immanuel Quickley
playerOutlook: Quickley entered last season fresh off finishing second place in the Sixth Man of the Year vote the year before, and for the first 30 games he maintained that same role off the bench for the Knicks. At that point, he was traded to the Raptors and became their starting point guard, averaging new career bests for the final 38 games of the season: 18.6 PPG, 6.8 APG, 4.8 RPG and 2.8 3PG. As a key part of the Raptors' young nucleus, Quickley has upside to reach and surpass those levels, giving him a floor of top-60 fantasy hoops prospect and an even higher ceiling.

name: Brandon Miller
playerOutlook: After a relatively slow start to his rookie campaign, Miller exploded in the New Year and averaged 20.3 PPG in the 35 games from the end of January until April 10. A lanky wing with size and a game reminiscent of a young Kevin Durant, Miller has significant upside as a shooter/scorer as soon as this season. Playing next to the offensive creation of LaMelo Ball and the inside/out presence of Miles Bridges, along with two other defensive role player starters, Miller should get plenty of good looks both from range and in the paint as a sophomore.

name: Evan Mobley
playerOutlook: Mobley finished third in the Defensive Player of the Year vote as a sophomore, then made incremental improvements in year 3. Most of those improvements centered around scoring efficiency, where he set new career-marks of 58.0 FG%, 71.9 FT% and 37.3 3P%. Mobley and Jarrett Allen form one of the best defensive combos in the league, and both of them operate well as finishers off the creation of Darius Garland and Donovan Mitchell. Fresh off signing a max extension this offseason, Mobley should continue to improve and has the potential to make a leap toward  stardom.

name: Darius Garland
playerOutlook: Garland has sacrificed the most since Donovan Mitchell joined the Cavaliers, with his scoring, assists and 3-pointers dropping in each of the past two seasons. With Mitchell and Evan Mobley both signing long-term extensions this offseason, it isn't clear that Garland's role will get any larger any time soon. He is still a strong  offense creator and top-75 fantasy hoops producer, but is unlikely to reach his upper-tier upside unless injury or trade creates a larger role for him.

name: Kyle Kuzma
playerOutlook: In his three seasons with the Wizards, Kuzma has settled in as the Wizards' best player and most consistent scorer. Over the last two, he has averaged within decimal points of 22 PPG, 7 RPG and 4 APG while making more than two 3-pointers and almost a steal and block per game. Though a veteran player, Kuzma is still only 29 years old and will pair with Jonas Valunciunas to give the team a relatively veteran frontcourt around rookie sensation Alex Sarr. If his minutes remain in the range they have been, Kuzma should continue to produce at a similar level in this season as well.

name: Anfernee Simons
playerOutlook: Simons is a gifted young scorer and offense creator on a team deep in rebuilding mode, coming off a season in which he transitioned into the full-time lead role, and at 25 years old is approaching his athletic peak. This is a combination that has a chance to vault Simons to among the leading offense producers in the league. He flashed his potential in stretches last season, like the month of December where he averaged 28.0 PPG, 5.4 APG and 4.0 3PG, or the nine games between March 2 and March 18 where he posted 27.4 PPG, 7.1 APG and 4.3 3PG. If Simons can put it all together and stay healthy...he has missed major time in four straight seasons and five of his six overall...he has the upside to outperform his current top-65 fantasy rankings and jump more into the top-50.

name: Klay Thompson
playerOutlook: Thompson split up the Splash Brothers this offseason, choosing to sign with the Mavericks as a free agent. At age 34, he is coming off his lowest scoring season since his sophomore campaign in 2012-13. Thompson's shooting struggles in the first half of the season led to him eventually being demoted to sixth man, but even then he remained one fo the best shooters in the league with 3.5 3PG on 38.7 3P%. Playing off Luka Doncic and Kyrie Irving, Thompson should be in for the most open looks he's had in years, if not ever, so he still has some bounce-back potential even later in his career.

name: Buddy Hield
playerOutlook: Hield has played for three teams in the last three seasons, but for the two most recent stops with the Pacers and 76ers, Hield played as more of a role player shooter off the bench. In his previous stop, with the Kings, Hield played a similar role but had more scoring responsibility and scored in the upper-teens with more than three 3-pointers per game on average. The latter may be more representative of his new role with his fourth team in four years, the Warriors. Even if he comes off the bench, Hield's scoring will be necessary on a Warriors team that lacks a second consistent scoring option behind Stephen Curry. Hield's volume 3-pointers are more valuable in category leagues, where he ranks in the top-65, than in points leagues where he's more like top-80.

name: Daniel Gafford
playerOutlook: Gafford is a high-efficiency, low-volume double-double threat with strong defensive numbers, averaging about two blocks and a steal per game. His 72.5 FG% led the NBA, and with both Luka Doncic and Kyrie Irving creating easy looks for him he should continue to finish lobs and bunnies at the rim all season. The biggest question mark is the size of his role, with Derrick Lively coming off an impressive rookie campaign and looking for bigger opportunities with a similar interior-based skillset that doesn't allow for simultaneous deployment.

name: Walker Kessler
playerOutlook: Kessler was once seen as one of the brightest young centers in the league, but he had a sophomore slump last season. He averaged 8.1 PPG, 7.5 RPG and 2.4 BPG. Kessler can be a great source of rebounds and blocks, especially in the later rounds, but the big question is whether he can elevate his offensive game this season, which could lead to more playing time. He's a gamble for fantasy managers this season.

name: Zion Williamson
playerOutlook: In the five seasons since Williamson was drafted number one overall in 2019, he has played in more than 29 games only twice. One of those was last season, when he played a career-high 70 games. On the downside, Williamson's averages of 22.9 PPG, 5.8 RPG, 57.0 FG% and 0.1 3PG all represented career lows. Williamson will look to bounce-back on the production front this season, and the fact that he'll get to play with a legitimate, All-Star point guard in Dejounte Murray could play a part in that. Murray should be able to get Williamson the ball in spots that he prefers, at times when the defense is more imbalanced having to account for the other Pelicans scoring threats. Questions about durability lower Williamson's fantasy hoops ranking to top-40 in points leagues, but those concerns in addition to his relative lack of blocks, steals and 3-pointers drop him to top-70 in category league rankings.

name: Coby White
playerOutlook: White got extra opportunity last season due to injuries to the Bulls backcourt and took full advantage, starting 78 games and setting new career highs in every major category on his way to finishing second in the Most Improved Player award. White played his best ball from around Thanksgiving until an injury in mid-March, averaging 22.1 PPG, 5.8 APG, 5.5 RPG and 3.1 3PG over a 47-game span. With leading scorer DeMar DeRozan no longer on the team, White is poised to continue his breakout this season.

name: Zach LaVine
playerOutlook: LaVine is one of ht best shooter-scorers in the NBAâ€¦when healthy. He followed up making a career-high 77 starts in the 2022-23 season with a career-low 23 starts last season, more akin to the 153 total games he missed in the previous five seasons. After averaging five-year lows in scoring, assists and 3-pointers last season, LaVine will look to bounce-back to his usual levels (25.5 PPG, 4.5 APG and 3.0 3PG in previous three seasons) in this campaign. LaVine had foot surgery in February but was fully cleared to play in June and iis presumed healthy entering camp.

name: Bogdan Bogdanovic
playerOutlook: Bogdanovic has been a staple in the Sixth Man of the Year vote in recent seasons, but moves to the starting lineup in the wake of the Dejounte Murray trade. Bogdanovic is a strong shooter-scorer on the wing that is also comfortable creating off the bounce. He started 33 games last season, mainly when Trae Young was injured, but his splits were very similar starting vs off the bench. He should get more minutes as a starter, though, increasing his opportunities and landing him in the top-90 fantasy prospects in points leagues.

name: Jusuf Nurkic
playerOutlook: Nurkic was the only proven starting caliber big man on the Suns last season after they traded away their size and depth to acquire Kevin Durant and Bradley Beal. Nurkic responded by averaging a double-double for the fourth time in his career, and the second time int he last three seasons. More importantly, he was availailable: his 76 games played were his most since the 2017-18 season, and the second-most in his career. Nurkic will again be asked to carry a heavy interior load for the Suns, and even with a more established backup center in Mason Plumlee, Nurkic should get as many minutes and as much opportunity as he can handle. He also adds about a block and a steal per game, and two seasons ago averaged almost a 3-pointer as well, and these contributions make him a slightly better fantasy hoops prospect in category leagues, inside the top-75, than in points leagues where he's more like top-80.

name: Michael Porter Jr.
playerOutlook: Porter set career best marks in two very important categories last season: minutes  played and games played. Porter played starter minutes, 31.7 MPG, but more impressively played in 81 games. The latter shattered his previous best of 62 games, set the season before. Porter has always had elite talent, but back injuries caused him to fall in the 2019 NBA Draft and forced him to miss 121 games during his first four seasons so his new durability is major...if he can sustain it. On the court, he is a lanky 6-10 forward that has one of the purest, high-efficiency shooting strokes in the NBA. Porter is a plus scorer and has developed into a plus rebounder for a small forward as well. He has also averaged almost three 3-pointers over the last two seasons, giving him slightly more value as a top-75 category-league prospect vs a top-80 prospect in points leagues.

name: Franz Wagner
playerOutlook: Wagner has increased his points, rebounds, assists and steals every season of his career to-date, and moving into season four this trend would see him surpass 20 PPG as a legit 20/5/5 option. Still only 23 years old, Wagner joins Paolo Banchero as one of the best young forward duos in the Eastern Conference. Wagner also contributes more than a 3-pointer and steal per game, but he doesn't block a lot of shots, so a bounce-back to closer to two treys per game would help his category rankings. He is currently a top-60 prospect in points leagues, but closer to top-75 in category leagues.

name: Pascal Siakam
playerOutlook: Siakam was traded from the Raptors to the Pacers in midseason, but his overall numbers remained largely unchanged. His assists dropped slightly, with the Pacers' distribution more concentrated in the hands of their point guard, but his rebounds went up a bit with no other strong rebounders in the starting unit. Siakam's scoring efficiency went up with the Pacers, and it could go up even further when he gets to play with a fully healthy Tyrese Haliburton. Siakam doesn't contribute much to steals or blocks these days, and he only makes about a 3-pointer a night, so his category-league ranking is much lower than his top-20 points ranking.

name: Devin Vassell
playerOutlook: Vassell has quietly established himself as the second core member of the Spurs' future, increasing his scoring and assist averages in every season of his four-year career up to almost 20 and 4 last season. Vassell can shoot off the dribble, but his efficiency is much higher off the spot-up. Particularly when opposing defense are focused on stopping Victor Wembanyama, who also happens to be a plus passer to open teammates. Vassel's scoring efficiency exploded, up more than three percentage points to 47.2 percent from the field. With better lead guard play this season, from both Chris Paul and rookie Stephon Castle, Vassell should see even more good looks and have a chance for the best scoring season of his career. Vassell is dealing with a foot injury that puts his early season into question, so durability is a concern, but he still projects as a borderline top-75 prospect in both points and category leagues.

name: Bradley Beal
playerOutlook: After 11 seasons with the Wizards, Beal joined Devin Booker and Kevin Durant to form a Big Three in Phoenix. At least, that was the plan. Injuries took away 29 of Beal's games, and when he did play his role as the junior-most scorer of the three didn't allow him to produce anywhere near his typical numbers. Beal settled in as an upper-mid teens scorer that contributes 9 - 10 combined assists and rebounds, a couple of threes and a steal per game. But he has missed 103 games in the last three seasons, so those numbers combined with durability concerns drop him to eighth or ninth round value in fantasy hoops drafts.

name: P.J. Washington
playerOutlook: Washington was a key trade deadline pickup for the Mavericks last season, playing a big role in their 2024 NBA Finals run. After coming over from the Hornets, he averaged 11.7 PPG, 6.2 RPG, 1.5 APG, 1.2 SPG, and 1.0 BPG. Heâ€™s expected to start this season, with projections showing similar stats. Over the summer, he worked on his ball handling and made adjustments to his shot. Thatâ€™s key because with new addition Klay Thompson drawing off-ball attention, Washington should get open looks. Heâ€™s a good late-round draft target.

name: Amen Thompson
playerOutlook: Thompson, the fourth overall pick in the 2023 NBA Draft, was in the midst of an impressive debut in the Las Vegas Summer League when he injured his ankle. The injury cost him the rest of the offseason and 19 games in the regular season, getting his rookie campaign off to a slower start in a role off the bench. Later in the season, though, Thompson got 23 starts and showed more of his potential with averages of 13.5 PPG (58.4 FG%, 68.8 FT%), 9.9 RPG, 3.7 APG, and 2.0 combined blocks and steals in 30.7 MPG. It isn't clear whether Thompson will be able to overtake starter Dillon Brooks, or even how well he will hold off fellow youngsters like Cam Whitmore and Reed Sheppard for minutes, but Thompson's upside if he earns starter minutes make him a worthy mid-late round fantasy hoops pick.

name: OG Anunoby
playerOutlook: Anunoby made a solid impact for the Knicks last season, even though he didnâ€™t play many games. In case you forgot, the Knicks traded RJ Barrett and Immanuel Quickley to the Raptors for him. Despite only playing 23 games with his new team after the trade, Anunoby averaged 14.1 PPG, 4.4 RPG, 1.5 APG and 1.7 SPG in 34.9 minutes per game. The Knicks had a 20-3 record in those games, showing how valuable Anunoby is to the rotation when healthy. Heâ€™s expected to post similar numbers this season as a key member of the Knicksâ€™ rotation, making him a player worth keeping on your radar late in your draft.

name: Jimmy Butler
playerOutlook: Butler has made a name for himself as "Playoffs Himmy", when he dramatically increases his scoring, rebound and steal numbers. But, during the regular season, the 35-year old Butler seems to pace himself. He plays fewer minutes, has lower averages and has not played more than 65 games in a season since 2016-17. This year could be different, though. Butler has reportedly asked for a contract extension and Heat President Pat Riley has publicly criticized some of Butler's actions. As such, in essentially a contract year, it's possible Playoffs Himmy makes some regular season appearances.

name: Tyler Herro
playerOutlook: Herro has been statistically the same player for the last three seasons, averaging within decimal points of the same number of points, rebounds, assists, 3-pointers, steals, blocks and field goal percentages. The only difference is the number of games played; Herro missed 40 games last season, whereas he missed between 15 and 18 every other season of his career. Durability is therefore an issue, but with his level of production he still makes solid value around the eighth or ninth round of fantasy hoops drafts.

name: Keegan Murray
playerOutlook: Murray followed up his All Rookie campaign with a better effort last season, notching incremental improvements in every category. Murray is a pure finisher, with fewer than two assists and one turnover per game because he rarely dribbles or passes. Murray continues to grow into his role as a stretch four, knocking down 3-pointers created mainly by teammates Domantas Sabonis and De'Aaron Fox. With another new teammate, DeMar DeRozan, also able to draw defensive attention and pass to open teammates, Murray should be even more efficient as a knock-down shooter in Year 3. He is a top-100 prospect in points leagues, but his 3-point volume and averages of around a steal and block per game boost him into the top 85 for category leagues.

name: Jarrett Allen
playerOutlook: Allen is coming off his best offensive season, with career-high averages of 16.5 PPG and 2.7 APG to go along with his typical double-digit boards and a block-plus per game. Allen is one of the most efficient scorers in the league with five straight seasons shooting over 61-percent from the field, and he operates well offf his teammates as a finisher on offense and the defensive anchor on defense. At 26 years old, Allen is just approaching his athletic peak so the best could be ahead.

name: Brandon Ingram
playerOutlook: Ingram is entering his sixth season with the Pelicans, and has averaged at least 20 PPG in each of the previous five. Last season marked his lowest scoring volume at in New Orleans at 20.8 PPG, but he did shoot his highest field goal percentage at 49.2%. The lower volume was likely a result of playing the majority of the season with two other heavy scorers in Zion WIlliamson and CJ McCollum, but if so that bodes ill for this season since a fourth plus scorer is joining the team in Dejounte Murray. Murray is a true point guard who could get Ingram in better positions to score more efficiently, but he also probably eats into Ingram's shot volume and also his assist opportunities after Ingram averaged 5.7 APG over the last three seasons. Ingram's name has been in some trade rumors, and if he ends up getting traded he could end up in a more advantageous situation to maximize volume. But, based on the scenario in New Orleans he projects to a top-75 play in points leagues but only a top-85 play in category leagues due to his lack of defensive statistical contributions.

name: Donovan Clingan
playerOutlook: Clingan was picked No. 7 overall in the NBA draft after leading the UConn to another National Championship. However, Portland has a crowded center rotation, featuring Deandre Ayton and Robert Williams III, among others. Clingan averaged 13.0 points, 7.4 rebounds and 2.5 blocks in his final season at UConn, which may not immediately suggest top-tier fantasy center potential. That said, he managed those numbers while playing just 22.5 MPG. The depth at center could make it tough for Clingan to secure significant playing time right away, but he has a chance to become a solid source of rebounds and blocks if an opportunity arises for additional minutes.

name: Isaiah Hartenstein
playerOutlook: Hartenstein parlayed a career-season with the Knicks into a new contract and starting center gig with the Thunder. Hartenstein's size, athleticism and surprisingly good passing ability from the pivot will allow Chet Holmgren to move to the power forward this season. In 49 starts for the Knicks last season, Hartenstein averaged a rounded 9 points, 9 rebounds and 3 assists with more than 2.5 combined blocks and steals while shooting 66 percent from the field and 74 percent from the line. That type of low-volume, high-efficiency double-double threat with strong defensive numbers would be enough for Hartenstein to sneak into the top-100 of both the points and category rankings entering the season.

name: Austin Reaves
playerOutlook: Reaves grew into his role as a full-time starter last season, showing clear improvements for the third season in a row and establishing more upside as a shooter-scorer and secondary lead guard on the Lakers. Reaves turned in strong scoring and assist numbers last season, even with LeBron Davis and Anthony Davis turning in their most durable seasons in years. But as they continue to get older, Reaves is becoming the younger generation player who is stepping into larger responsibilities. The likelihood of continued improvement boosts Reaves into a top-70 valuation in points leagues, but his lack of blocks and steals pushes his draft stock down a round or two in category leagues.

name: Grayson Allen
playerOutlook: Allen had a career year with the Suns, leading the league in 3-point percentage at 46.1%. He posted career highs in FGA (9.1), PPG (13.5), RPG (3.9), and APG (3.0). With the Suns addressing their point guard issue by signing Tyus Jones, Allenâ€™s role should stay the same. If you're looking for points or threes in the later rounds, don't overlook him.

name: Naz Reid
playerOutlook: Reid won the league's Sixth Man of the Year award last season, making him the first Timberwolves player to do so. He had career highs across the board, averaging 13.5 PPG, 5.2 RPG, 1.3 APG, 1.0 BPG and 1.0 SPG. This season, Reid should keep a similar role and production level with the Timberwolves, as the team moves on from Karl-Anthony Towns and goes with Julius Randle in the frontcourt. Reid is definitely someone to watch as you approach the double-digit rounds in your draft.

name: Draymond Green
playerOutlook: Green remains the anchor of the Warriorsâ€™ frontcourt, averaging 8.6 PPG, 7.2 RPG, 6.0 APG, 1.0 SPG and 1.0 BPG last season. He's still an excellent facilitator and pushes the pace in transition. Health and availability are the biggest concerns for Green. Heâ€™s projected for similar per-game stats this year and could see slightly more usage with Klay Thompson gone. Keep Green on your radar in the late rounds as a solid source of assists from a frontcourt position.

name: Cam Thomas
playerOutlook: Thomas has shown his pure scoring ability in spurts in each of the last two seasons, and is now poised to become the number one option for the Nets after the Mikal Bridges trade. Thomas averaged 27.1 PPG on 20.6 FGA over 17 games after returning from injury in March last season, and this season he could maintain or even increase that shot share on a Nets squad without many scoring options.

name: Terry Rozier
playerOutlook: Rozier was traded to the Heat mid-season, and his role shrunk from the best offensive option on a lottery-bound Hornets team to one of several talented scorers on the Heat. He is still a solid producer, scoring in the upper-mid teens, combining for almost nine assists and blocks, hitting a couple of threes and grabbing a steal per game. Numbers good enough for draft consideration around the ninth or tenth round of fantasy basketball drafts.

name: Josh Giddey

Giddey fell out of favor last season, averaging career-lows across the board in only 25.2 MPG. If he earns starting minutes for the Bulls, he could bounce-back to or surpass the career-best marks of 16.6 PPG and 7.9 RPG with 6.2 APG he set the previous season.

name: Kristaps Porzingis

The Celtics' offense has so many threats that defenses can't focus on Porzingis, allowing the two lead guards on the team to put him in position to score efficiently. Porzingis' combination of scoring and, shooting (1.9 3PG) and defense (1.9 BPG, 0.7 SPG) is very fantasy-friendly, particularly in points-based leagues, but the big question mark is availability. Porzingis has missed at least 15 games every season since his rookie year, averaging almost 24 absences without even factoring in his entire missed season in 2018-19.

name: Jabari Smith Jr.

name: Reed Sheppard

name: DeMar DeRozan

With Domantas Sabonis as the main offensive hub and De'Aaron Fox the creator off the dribble, DeRozan will slot in as a both a finisher and secondary distrubtor. His volume likely drops from the 25.5 PPG he averaged with the Bulls, but he should get good looks and imbalanced defenses so he has a chance to challenge his scoring efficiency record of 53.1 FG% from 2019-20. Even in his lesser role, DeRozan remains a top-100 prospect in fantasy hoops.

playerOutlook: Poeltl is a nightly double-double threat, a low-volume but high-efficiency scorer who also has five straight seasons with more than two combined blocks and steals per game. Poeltl is a high-floor/low-ceiling prospect in fantasy hoops leagues, right on the borderline of the top-100.

name: Josh Hart

name: Khris Middleton

At 33, he's the Bucks' third option behind Giannis Antetokounmpo and Damian Lillard and he could be a sleeper late in fantasy drafts in both category and points formats. However, his extensive injury history makes him a risky pick and his best days as a fantasy standout are behind him.

name: Malcolm Brogdon

name: Russell Westbrook

Westbrook has finished in the top-10 of the NBA Sixth Man of the Year vote in each of the last two seasons, and has proven capable of averaging double-digit points with solid contributions in assists, rebounds, steals and even a 3-pointer per game off the bench. On the Nuggets, Westbrook will likely assume some of the role and minutes left by the departed Kentavious Caldwell-Pope and have more opportunity to produce than he did with the Clippers last season.

name: Jonas Valanciunas
playerOutlook: Valanciunas joins a Wizards team deep in rebuilding mode, putting him in an interesting situation. He is arguably the best player on the team, but at a mature 32 years old he could eventually have to make way for younger players like 2024 2nd overall pick Alex Sarr to shine. But, when he's on the court, Valanciunas is an efficient scorer who once averaged 20 PPG and gathers double-digit rebounds on a pretty much nightly basis. If called upon as a team anchor to help show the younger players how to be professional, Valanciunas could be in for a big year on a talent-depleted squad.

name: Marcus Smart
playerOutlook: Smart is heading into his second season with the Grizzlies after an injury-filled 2023-24 campaign where he was limited to just 20 games. The veteran guard contributes across the board with points, assists, rebounds, threes and steals. While Ja Morant will likely continue to command a high usage rate, Smart is projected to have the fifth-most fantasy points on the team.

name: Ausar Thompson

But in 20 games where he played 32 or more minutes, those numbers jumped to 12.3 PPG, 8.6 RPG, 3.0 APG, 1.6 SPG and 1.6 BPG. name: Stephon Castle

name: Mark Williams
playerOutlook: Williams took major steps as a sophomore, averaging a rounded 13-point, 10-rebound double-double with about a block and a steal in 27 MPG. Unfortunately, he only played 19 games in his second season after only playing 43 as a rookie due to injury, most severely to his back. Williams suffered a tendon strain in his foot late in September and his health entering the season is unclear, but when he's on the court Williams is the kind of high-efficiency, double-double machine with defensive upside that produces strong value in category leagues.

name: Trayce Jackson-Davis
playerOutlook: Jackson-Davis burst onto the scene as a surprise contributor as a rookie, earning rotation and eventually starter minutes despite being drafted at the back of the second round. In his 16 starts, Jackson-Davis flirted with averaging a double-double with 11.3 PPG, 7.6 RPG and almost 2.5 combined blocks and steals while shooting 69.6 percent from the floor. Jackson-Davis has had an excellent training camp and is vying for the starting center spot as a sophomore. If he earns the role, or at least the minutes, he projects as a top-100 prospect in points leagues and just outside the top-100, closer to 110th, in category leagues.

One area he could improve is on defense, where his size and explosiveness could help him develop into a plus shot-blocker as well. Duren enters the season as a top-80 prospect in points leagues but his lack of blocked shots slides him down just outside the top 100 in categories leagues.
